AUDIENCE: How do you
come combat and deal

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:04.090
with people who have violently
opposed views to you, even

00:33:04.090 --> 00:33:06.910
on base principles, and then
get to talking policy with them

00:33:06.910 --> 00:33:10.680
afterwards if their base
beliefs are different?

00:33:10.680 --> 00:33:13.570
WENDY DAVIS: There are some
people that you can't talk to.

00:33:13.570 --> 00:33:16.576
I know that's not a very
constructive answer.

00:33:19.180 --> 00:33:23.140
In my legislative experience,
for example, I really

00:33:23.140 --> 00:33:26.440
prided myself on
working across the aisle

00:33:26.440 --> 00:33:30.310
and got quite a lot of
legislation passed doing that.

00:33:30.310 --> 00:33:32.260
You have to do that in Texas.

00:33:32.260 --> 00:33:37.570
It's a quite predominantly
Republican place.

00:33:37.570 --> 00:33:41.410
But there are some areas where
it's worth drawing that line,

00:33:41.410 --> 00:33:46.030
where you can't find
a way to compromise.

00:33:46.030 --> 00:33:47.470
And I think the
most effective way

00:33:47.470 --> 00:33:50.260
to communicate when you're
in that place, or any

00:33:50.260 --> 00:33:54.130
of these places actually, even
where you do find that middle,

00:33:54.130 --> 00:34:00.790
is to do it through personal
experiences and human stories.

00:34:00.790 --> 00:34:03.070
A lot of times, we have
these conversations

00:34:03.070 --> 00:34:06.940
up in the ethereal
world and we're

00:34:06.940 --> 00:34:11.320
stuck in our own ideological
way of thinking about them.

00:34:11.320 --> 00:34:13.750
But when we can
make them more real,

00:34:13.750 --> 00:34:15.100
it really makes a difference.

00:34:15.100 --> 00:34:19.480
So a great example of how
that can move the ball.

00:34:19.480 --> 00:34:24.159
In the conversation
around LGBTQ equality,

00:34:24.159 --> 00:34:29.590
that really began to move
when a great deal of work

00:34:29.590 --> 00:34:33.010
was done determining
how to talk about it.

00:34:33.010 --> 00:34:35.409
And to talk about
it in a way that

00:34:35.409 --> 00:34:37.929
was more resonant than
had been the case.

00:34:37.929 --> 00:34:41.760
It had been talked about
specifically as equality.

00:34:41.760 --> 00:34:43.690
And that we all ought
to care about it just

00:34:43.690 --> 00:34:46.230
to be living in a
full and equal world

00:34:46.230 --> 00:34:49.179
and that we all ought
to be treated that way.

00:34:49.179 --> 00:34:52.120
But the conversation
shifted, purposefully so,

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:54.010
to be much more personal.

00:34:54.010 --> 00:34:57.520
And a lot of work actually was
done in your state around that.

00:34:57.520 --> 00:34:59.800
Door-to-door
conversations with people

00:34:59.800 --> 00:35:04.330
were had where couples
who were impacted

00:35:04.330 --> 00:35:07.690
by the inequality of marriage
equality, for example,

00:35:07.690 --> 00:35:13.150
would go to an older
Republican household and say,

00:35:13.150 --> 00:35:16.510
we want to talk to you about
why this matters to us.

00:35:16.510 --> 00:35:21.070
It really shifted people's
thinking about it.

00:35:21.070 --> 00:35:24.390
And it's because
it became personal

00:35:24.390 --> 00:35:27.085
and because they saw it
as something personal.

00:35:29.800 --> 00:35:31.230
Storytelling is powerful.

00:35:31.230 --> 00:35:33.580
And I love seeing the
fact that it's becoming

00:35:33.580 --> 00:35:35.270
more and more prominent.

00:35:35.270 --> 00:35:38.710
That technology has provided
such a great platform

00:35:38.710 --> 00:35:42.520
for people to share stories
and to influence based on that.

00:35:42.520 --> 00:35:48.780
A lot of abortion story-sharing
going on online post-2013

00:35:48.780 --> 00:35:51.870
in the filibuster and
people's consciousness

00:35:51.870 --> 00:35:53.420
raising about that.

00:35:53.420 --> 00:35:56.310
And I think that's
our most effective way

00:35:56.310 --> 00:35:58.470
to try to get through
hard conversations.

00:35:58.470 --> 00:36:01.530
But that doesn't mean everyone's
always going to listen.

