00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:46.397
are seeing a revitalization in
interest in politics and people

00:40:46.397 --> 00:40:47.105
getting involved.

00:40:50.240 --> 00:40:55.220
My question is,
you also see women

00:40:55.220 --> 00:40:58.250
voting against their own
interests a lot of the time.

00:40:58.250 --> 00:41:02.610
And I feel like it is because
they just focus on one issue.

00:41:02.610 --> 00:41:05.450
How can we make it a
larger conversation

00:41:05.450 --> 00:41:07.640
so that they actually,
perhaps, want

00:41:07.640 --> 00:41:11.930
to start supporting each
other rather than tearing

00:41:11.930 --> 00:41:14.367
each other down?

00:41:14.367 --> 00:41:16.700
WENDY DAVIS: I like the way
you ended that last question

00:41:16.700 --> 00:41:19.370
because it made me think
of something that Chelsea

00:41:19.370 --> 00:41:22.640
Handler said recently about
women, that we've been taught

00:41:22.640 --> 00:41:25.040
to tackle, not to climb.

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:28.610
And I do think sometimes we
can be each other's own worst

00:41:28.610 --> 00:41:31.460
enemy because there's a lot
of judgment that goes on.

00:41:31.460 --> 00:41:34.140
Depending on the choices that
we've made in our own lives

00:41:34.140 --> 00:41:37.310
and careers, or whether that
career is outside the home

00:41:37.310 --> 00:41:39.890
or inside the home.

00:41:39.890 --> 00:41:43.580
This is the $20 million
question, though.

00:41:43.580 --> 00:41:46.040
How do we make sure that
people aren't voting

00:41:46.040 --> 00:41:48.390
against their own interests?

00:41:48.390 --> 00:41:50.480
And there's a lot
of education that

00:41:50.480 --> 00:41:53.882
needs to take place
because people aren't going

00:41:53.882 --> 00:41:55.340
to vote against
their own interests

00:41:55.340 --> 00:41:58.040
because they think they're
voting against their interests.

00:41:58.040 --> 00:42:00.289
They really believe they're
voting in their interests,

00:42:00.289 --> 00:42:01.730
right?

00:42:01.730 --> 00:42:05.090
And I think Democrats
have failed,

00:42:05.090 --> 00:42:10.670
myself included,
in doing a good job

00:42:10.670 --> 00:42:15.290
of communicating why it is that
our values are ones that really

00:42:15.290 --> 00:42:20.680
are more in alignment with
most people's in this country.

00:42:20.680 --> 00:42:24.050
And there's a lot of work
being done right now on,

00:42:24.050 --> 00:42:25.670
how do we reframe the narrative?

00:42:25.670 --> 00:42:28.850
And how do we do a better
job of talking about that?

00:42:28.850 --> 00:42:30.840
But back to that
personal storytelling

00:42:30.840 --> 00:42:37.910
again, where we have
experiences that we

00:42:37.910 --> 00:42:40.580
can share with people
who may disagree with us

00:42:40.580 --> 00:42:44.780
and paint a picture of a
real person and an impact

00:42:44.780 --> 00:42:47.810
that would feel more
compelling to them.

00:42:47.810 --> 00:42:49.890
Where you have
opportunities to do that,

00:42:49.890 --> 00:42:52.880
I think that's the most powerful
way to cut through that.

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:54.440
And particularly,
if there's a way

00:42:54.440 --> 00:42:57.500
to paint within their
own perspective what's

00:42:57.500 --> 00:43:00.680
happening to them
vis-a-vis a person

00:43:00.680 --> 00:43:02.570
that they may have
thought was actually

00:43:02.570 --> 00:43:06.095
aligned with their interests.

00:43:06.095 --> 00:43:08.351
AUDIENCE: First of all, I
agree with the optimism.

00:43:08.351 --> 00:43:10.100
And I think that's
just because everyone's

00:43:10.100 --> 00:43:11.570
having such a big wake-up call.

00:43:11.570 --> 00:43:14.870
So when I came to this country
four years ago from London,

00:43:14.870 --> 00:43:17.090
I was maybe a latent feminist.

00:43:17.090 --> 00:43:19.830
I've always believed
in equality, et cetera,

00:43:19.830 --> 00:43:21.140
but it wasn't an issue for me.

00:43:21.140 --> 00:43:23.389
And then I came to the Valley,
