00:43:38.307 --> 00:43:39.890
of people who just
didn't care anymore

00:43:39.890 --> 00:43:41.510
and didn't seem to be
caring about politics

00:43:41.510 --> 00:43:42.250
have been awakened.

00:43:42.250 --> 00:43:44.708
So I actually think this might
turn out to be a good thing.

00:43:44.708 --> 00:43:46.160
I'm sharing the optimism.

00:43:46.160 --> 00:43:49.880
But I wanted to ask
you about this question

00:43:49.880 --> 00:43:53.420
about personal storytelling,
which I totally understand,

00:43:53.420 --> 00:43:55.310
in terms of building tolerance.

00:43:55.310 --> 00:43:59.120
If you're relating to this
person, it's different.

00:43:59.120 --> 00:44:01.610
And it reminds me when I was
16, I was in upstate New York

00:44:01.610 --> 00:44:06.350
as an exchange student in
a family that was un-eco,

00:44:06.350 --> 00:44:08.630
blatantly racist,
all these things.

00:44:08.630 --> 00:44:12.800
And so my dad would shout at
black people out of this pickup

00:44:12.800 --> 00:44:13.400
truck--

00:44:13.400 --> 00:44:15.140
my host dad.

00:44:15.140 --> 00:44:17.420
But then, Bob, who
was the black guy who

00:44:17.420 --> 00:44:20.980
worked with him,
somehow wasn't black

00:44:20.980 --> 00:44:23.390
because he was Bob,
because he knew him.

00:44:23.390 --> 00:44:26.780
So I think that's what
you're getting at, right?

00:44:26.780 --> 00:44:28.850
Once you know the
person, you can no longer

00:44:28.850 --> 00:44:32.210
put them into this
category of otherness.

00:44:32.210 --> 00:44:34.580
But on the flip side,
with the politicians,

00:44:34.580 --> 00:44:36.830
it seems like we're moving
further and further away

00:44:36.830 --> 00:44:40.280
from issues and more and more
about the personality, in that

00:44:40.280 --> 00:44:43.380
Trump got elected because
of his personality that

00:44:43.380 --> 00:44:45.659
appeals to TV viewers.

00:44:45.659 --> 00:44:47.450
And it was nothing
about the issues, right?

00:44:47.450 --> 00:44:49.710
Everyone ignored all the issues.

00:44:49.710 --> 00:44:52.880
So how can we
square those things?

00:44:52.880 --> 00:44:54.860
Should we get politics
away from personalities

00:44:54.860 --> 00:44:58.110
and more towards issues again,
or is that just impossible?

00:44:58.110 --> 00:45:00.206
WENDY DAVIS: I don't
know if that's possible.

00:45:00.206 --> 00:45:01.580
But I think a lot
of people, too,

00:45:01.580 --> 00:45:05.900
would tell you
that they supported

00:45:05.900 --> 00:45:08.990
Donald Trump because
they did believe

00:45:08.990 --> 00:45:11.090
that he was
supportive of policies

00:45:11.090 --> 00:45:13.730
that were going to have a
positive impact on their lives.

00:45:13.730 --> 00:45:16.250
So whether we were
talking about people

00:45:16.250 --> 00:45:18.710
who had been impacted
by automation,

00:45:18.710 --> 00:45:21.590
but he gave an easy
target to blame,

00:45:21.590 --> 00:45:26.144
which was an immigrant workforce
that had taken your job.

00:45:26.144 --> 00:45:27.560
Whether we're
talking about people

00:45:27.560 --> 00:45:31.940
who worked in industries
where environmental evolution

00:45:31.940 --> 00:45:34.550
and the protections
of environmental laws

00:45:34.550 --> 00:45:41.510
had decreased the
employment capacity

00:45:41.510 --> 00:45:44.480
in that particular sector and
they'd been impacted by that,

00:45:44.480 --> 00:45:49.310
they heard him speaking
to them about that.

00:45:49.310 --> 00:45:53.030
Never underestimate the
misogyny that is out there

00:45:53.030 --> 00:45:57.560
and even if it's not something
that people bring forward

00:45:57.560 --> 00:46:00.140
consciously, their
own subconscious

00:46:00.140 --> 00:46:03.620
feelings about the threat
that equality in the workforce

00:46:03.620 --> 00:46:07.220
means to their own
livelihoods and success,

00:46:07.220 --> 00:46:10.940
he spoke powerfully to
a lot of those things

00:46:10.940 --> 00:46:14.390
and people were
responding to them.

00:46:14.390 --> 00:46:17.570
But I love your example
about Bob, right?

00:46:17.570 --> 00:46:22.280
Because that's the only way
that we can really counter that.

00:46:22.280 --> 00:46:25.010
There was a great story
in "The New York Times"

00:46:25.010 --> 00:46:30.050
yesterday about a
Mexican gentleman

00:46:30.050 --> 00:46:34.400
who was detained recently
and he's probably

00:46:34.400 --> 00:46:36.230
going to be deported.

00:46:36.230 --> 00:46:41.229
And in this small Iowa
town, he was so well loved.

00:46:41.229 --> 00:46:42.770
And everyone's
saying, well, yeah, we

00:46:42.770 --> 00:46:49.490
support rounding up and
deporting, but not him.

00:46:49.490 --> 00:46:50.630
I think his name is Carlos.

00:46:50.630 --> 00:46:52.430
We love Carlos.

00:46:52.430 --> 00:46:55.160
And Carlos had done all
these incredible things

00:46:55.160 --> 00:46:57.530
in the community, like
supporting firefighters

00:46:57.530 --> 00:47:00.139
and always being the person
there with the food drives

00:47:00.139 --> 00:47:01.430
and different things like that.

00:47:01.430 --> 00:47:03.240
And everyone loves them.

00:47:03.240 --> 00:47:08.060
So making the reality
come to life for people

00:47:08.060 --> 00:47:10.460
is really a way to
take a step back

00:47:10.460 --> 00:47:14.210
and to look at
things differently.

00:47:14.210 --> 00:47:16.660
The real challenge
that we have is not

00:47:16.660 --> 00:47:18.950
that there are
personalities in politics

00:47:18.950 --> 00:47:26.360
that can be persuasive, but that
we have a media culture where

00:47:26.360 --> 00:47:28.820
people self-select the
prism through which they

00:47:28.820 --> 00:47:30.470
view their news.

00:47:30.470 --> 00:47:33.740
And they're going to hear
things and be told things

00:47:33.740 --> 00:47:37.100
very differently depending
on that self-selection.

00:47:37.100 --> 00:47:39.740
That, to me, is the greatest
challenge that we have,

00:47:39.740 --> 00:47:42.860
is cutting through
the version of things

00:47:42.860 --> 00:47:45.680
that you find on
different news sources.

00:47:45.680 --> 00:47:50.570
And the decisions
or the opinions

00:47:50.570 --> 00:47:54.740
that you form based on what you
hear coming from those filters.

00:47:54.740 --> 00:47:57.440
And we all owe a
responsibility, again,

00:47:57.440 --> 00:48:00.530
to take the power away
from their version

00:48:00.530 --> 00:48:05.510
and put the power into
a reality version that's

00:48:05.510 --> 00:48:08.810
based on real human impact.

00:48:08.810 --> 00:48:13.400
It's hard, but we're each
an influencer and we each

00:48:13.400 --> 00:48:19.260
have an opportunity to do it
to our spheres of influence.

00:48:19.260 --> 00:48:20.670
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:20.670 --> 00:48:22.430
I'm Monique.

00:48:22.430 --> 00:48:24.830
I'm an immigrant, a
woman, and a Latina.

00:48:24.830 --> 00:48:28.340
So I 100% relate to
your daughter's fears

00:48:28.340 --> 00:48:30.680
about what's going on.

00:48:30.680 --> 00:48:33.470
And on top of that,
like many others,

00:48:33.470 --> 00:48:36.730
I have the opposite
concern from hers.

00:48:36.730 --> 00:48:41.210
I'm raising a white male
in the Silicon Valley

00:48:41.210 --> 00:48:44.000
and I'm deeply
concerned about what

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:49.850
he's going to grow up listening
to at school and on the TV,

00:48:49.850 --> 00:48:51.290
and so on.

00:48:51.290 --> 00:48:52.910
It was very
frustrating not being

00:48:52.910 --> 00:48:56.270
able to vote last election.

00:48:56.270 --> 00:48:59.690
So I guess my question
to you would be,

00:48:59.690 --> 00:49:03.350
how do you think
we that do not get

00:49:03.350 --> 00:49:05.720
to vote in this country
can have the biggest

00:49:05.720 --> 00:49:07.865
impact beyond the ballots?

00:49:11.810 --> 00:49:14.000
WENDY DAVIS: In myriad of ways.

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:16.730
And again, find the thing
that feels most authentic

00:49:16.730 --> 00:49:20.420
and of value to you personally.

00:49:20.420 --> 00:49:24.080
If it's in the political space,
obviously supporting candidates

00:49:24.080 --> 00:49:26.510
and working for them, even
if you can't vote for them.

00:49:26.510 --> 00:49:31.490
For example in Texas, I had
a large number of Dreamers

00:49:31.490 --> 00:49:34.970
who worked really, really
hard on our campaign.

00:49:34.970 --> 00:49:37.310
None of whom could actually
vote for me, but all of whom

00:49:37.310 --> 00:49:40.820
had a vested stake in what
the outcome of that election

00:49:40.820 --> 00:49:44.120
looked like, and who cared
very deeply about the direction

00:49:44.120 --> 00:49:46.490
that we were going as a state.

00:49:46.490 --> 00:49:49.170
You have a wonderful
opportunity with your son

00:49:49.170 --> 00:49:51.630
to be an influencer
in the way he

00:49:51.630 --> 00:49:54.260
is going to view these issues.

00:49:54.260 --> 00:49:59.120
And I'm sure he's going
to grow up beautifully

00:49:59.120 --> 00:50:03.140
based on who you are and what
your values are and making sure

00:50:03.140 --> 00:50:06.290
that you pass those on to him.

00:50:06.290 --> 00:50:08.960
If you find yourself
really deeply

00:50:08.960 --> 00:50:14.950
passionate about LGBT equality,
or the environment, or gender

00:50:14.950 --> 00:50:18.380
equality, find an organization
that matters to you

00:50:18.380 --> 00:50:20.390
and support the
work that they do.

00:50:20.390 --> 00:50:23.720
And ask them how you can
be valuable to the work

00:50:23.720 --> 00:50:25.110
that they do.

00:50:25.110 --> 00:50:28.310
There's so much that's
needed, in terms

00:50:28.310 --> 00:50:34.490
of our time and our
passion that, as long

00:50:34.490 --> 00:50:37.670
as you find a place that
feels meaningful to you,

00:50:37.670 --> 00:50:39.575
you will be making a difference.

00:50:39.575 --> 00:50:43.597
You really will, whether you
can ultimately vote or not.

00:50:43.597 --> 00:50:45.680
SPEAKER 2: And Wendy, we're
going to take one more

00:50:45.680 --> 00:50:47.480
question from a man
who's been watching

00:50:47.480 --> 00:50:50.930
over the livestream who asked,
"How do you see the role of men

00:50:50.930 --> 00:50:52.070
as allies?

00:50:52.070 --> 00:50:54.040
What can we do to
help this cause?"

00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:56.480
WENDY DAVIS: That's a
really good question.

00:50:56.480 --> 00:50:59.420
First of all, I'll tell
you a story about myself

00:50:59.420 --> 00:51:03.650
and the word "feminism," back
to what was said earlier.

00:51:03.650 --> 00:51:05.270
When I was in my 30s
and I was running

00:51:05.270 --> 00:51:09.350
for city council for the first
time, I was asked by a reporter

00:51:09.350 --> 00:51:11.390
whether I was a feminist.

00:51:11.390 --> 00:51:14.630
And I answered the question no.

00:51:14.630 --> 00:51:17.600
And I'm ashamed to tell
you that, honestly.

00:51:17.600 --> 00:51:20.180
But I want to tell
you because I want

00:51:20.180 --> 00:51:23.090
us to do some self-exploration
about our own attitudes

00:51:23.090 --> 00:51:24.500
and perspectives.

00:51:24.500 --> 00:51:25.560
Why did I do that?

00:51:25.560 --> 00:51:29.000
Well, I felt like it
was categorizing me

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:32.600
in this limited way and
defining me in a way

00:51:32.600 --> 00:51:36.590
that other people would
look at and disqualify me

00:51:36.590 --> 00:51:39.530
based on that categorization.

00:51:39.530 --> 00:51:46.745
But by doing that, I was playing
a role in marginalizing women.

00:51:49.340 --> 00:51:51.750
What I would love
to see more of--

00:51:51.750 --> 00:51:55.550
and I'm so pleased to see
so much of it right now--

00:51:55.550 --> 00:51:58.460
are men stepping forward and
saying, I'm a feminist, too.

00:51:58.460 --> 00:52:00.200
Because to be a
feminist, really it just

00:52:00.200 --> 00:52:02.283
means that you support the
idea that we should all

00:52:02.283 --> 00:52:06.830
be equal in society
and the economy.

00:52:06.830 --> 00:52:08.990
What's that bumper sticker?

00:52:08.990 --> 00:52:12.830
Feminism is the radical notion
that women are human beings,

00:52:12.830 --> 00:52:15.450
or something like that.

00:52:15.450 --> 00:52:17.450
I'm really encouraged
about that, too, though,

00:52:17.450 --> 00:52:18.860
and where we are.

00:52:18.860 --> 00:52:22.070
The marches, the women's
marches that took place

00:52:22.070 --> 00:52:24.270
around the country
and around the world,

00:52:24.270 --> 00:52:25.640
there were so many men.

00:52:25.640 --> 00:52:28.580
There were so many
beautiful, wonderful men

00:52:28.580 --> 00:52:32.680
stepping forward and saying,
this matters to all of us.

00:52:32.680 --> 00:52:33.680
AUDIENCE: I'm with her.

00:52:33.680 --> 00:52:35.960
WENDY DAVIS: I'm
with her, exactly.

00:52:35.960 --> 00:52:39.230
And I think more men
are looking at this

00:52:39.230 --> 00:52:41.930
from the prism of their
mothers and their sisters

00:52:41.930 --> 00:52:43.670
and, especially,
their daughters,

00:52:43.670 --> 00:52:49.970
and wanting to create a world
where they have the opportunity

00:52:49.970 --> 00:52:53.780
to fulfill their
dreams and their best

00:52:53.780 --> 00:52:55.830
opportunities for themselves.

00:52:55.830 --> 00:52:59.450
And so more and more, we're
joining this conversation

00:52:59.450 --> 00:53:00.860
as one.

00:53:00.860 --> 00:53:02.570
And I think one of
the powerful ways

00:53:02.570 --> 00:53:07.190
that we can talk about it is
the fact that when we are all

00:53:07.190 --> 00:53:10.580
working toward gender equality,
we're actually all working

00:53:10.580 --> 00:53:14.570
to a place where our
economy has the strongest

00:53:14.570 --> 00:53:16.820
opportunity to thrive.

00:53:16.820 --> 00:53:19.250
And it really goes
back to looking

00:53:19.250 --> 00:53:21.740
at what happened when women
were able to really enter

00:53:21.740 --> 00:53:25.029
the workforce and stay in
the full-time workforce

00:53:25.029 --> 00:53:25.820
for the first time.

00:53:25.820 --> 00:53:27.260
It was in the 1970s.

00:53:27.260 --> 00:53:30.320
And I know a lot of the really
young people in this room

00:53:30.320 --> 00:53:31.630
cannot even fathom.

00:53:31.630 --> 00:53:35.900
But as of 1971, birth
control was illegal.

00:53:35.900 --> 00:53:39.680
If you were not married, you
could not have birth control.

00:53:39.680 --> 00:53:42.920
In 1972, with a
Supreme Court decision

00:53:42.920 --> 00:53:47.030
that's much less known than Roe
v. Wade, Eisenstadt v. Baird,

00:53:47.030 --> 00:53:49.730
birth control became legal
for unmarried persons, not

00:53:49.730 --> 00:53:50.716
just married persons.

00:53:50.716 --> 00:53:53.090
There had been a Supreme Court
decision a few years prior

00:53:53.090 --> 00:53:57.620
to that that allowed married
people to access birth control.

00:53:57.620 --> 00:54:00.470
So birth control and then,
of course, Roe v. Wade.

00:54:00.470 --> 00:54:03.830
With our right to
make determinations

00:54:03.830 --> 00:54:06.470
about our own bodies,
we could suddenly

00:54:06.470 --> 00:54:08.570
decide that we were going
to enter the workforce

00:54:08.570 --> 00:54:10.820
and we were going to stay
there if we wanted to.

00:54:10.820 --> 00:54:14.720
And the women's participation
rate in the workforce

00:54:14.720 --> 00:54:16.250
took this huge climb.

00:54:16.250 --> 00:54:19.580
It went from about
the low-20 percentile

00:54:19.580 --> 00:54:23.540
to the mid-40 percentile over
the course of the next three

00:54:23.540 --> 00:54:25.940
decades and hung there.

00:54:25.940 --> 00:54:30.290
And because it hung there,
we contributed significantly

00:54:30.290 --> 00:54:34.370
to the economic output the
economic growth of the country.

00:54:34.370 --> 00:54:40.730
About an estimated $1.7 trillion
in 2012, which pays for,

00:54:40.730 --> 00:54:45.380
by the way, Medicaid, Medicare,
and Social Security combined.

00:54:45.380 --> 00:54:49.670
Just our participation, our
increased participation,

00:54:49.670 --> 00:54:53.750
from the 1970s to that point
is responsible for being

00:54:53.750 --> 00:54:56.840
able to pay for all
of those programs.

00:54:56.840 --> 00:55:02.300
So we all have a vested stake
in women's equality and women

00:55:02.300 --> 00:55:06.320
being able to realize our
full economic participation

00:55:06.320 --> 00:55:07.700
in this country.

00:55:07.700 --> 00:55:12.360
And I want to hear more
women and men sharing that

00:55:12.360 --> 00:55:15.860
with their friends
and their coworkers.

00:55:15.860 --> 00:55:18.750
That this isn't
just a social issue.

00:55:18.750 --> 00:55:21.710
It's not just about saying,
we ought to treat everyone

00:55:21.710 --> 00:55:23.510
fairly and equally.

00:55:23.510 --> 00:55:25.400
We all have an
economic stake in it.

00:55:25.400 --> 00:55:28.320
And it goes back to that saying
that a lot of people think

00:55:28.320 --> 00:55:30.140
is just a trite,
little campaign saying.

00:55:30.140 --> 00:55:32.390
When women do better,
we all do better.

00:55:32.390 --> 00:55:34.080
It's really true.

00:55:34.080 --> 00:55:36.870
And so we all have not
only a stake in it,

00:55:36.870 --> 00:55:38.750
but we ought to be
exercising our voices

00:55:38.750 --> 00:55:40.670
and making sure that
we're spreading greater

00:55:40.670 --> 00:55:42.317
understanding about that.

00:55:42.317 --> 00:55:42.900
